===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|trewe|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|triewe|trīewe|lang=ang}}, (Mercian)  {{term|treowe|trēowe|lang=ang}} ‘trusty, faithful’, from {{proto|Germanic|triwwiz|lang=en}} (compare Dutch {{term|getrouw|lang=nl}} and {{term|trouw|lang=nl}}, German {{term|treu|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|trygg|lang=sv}} ‘safe, secure’), from pre-Germanic *''dreu̯h₂i̯os'', from {{proto|Indo-European|druh₂||dreu̯h₂|lang=en}} ‘steady, firm’ (compare Irish {{term|dearbh|lang=ga}} ‘sure’, Old Prussian {{term|druwis|lang=prg}} ‘faith’, Ancient Greek {{term||droós}} ‘firm’), extension of {{proto|Indo-European|title=|dóru|lang=en}} ‘tree’. More at [[tree]].<br />
For semantic development, compare Latin {{term|robustus|lang=la}} ‘tough’ from {{term|robur|lang=la}} ‘red oak’.

